VALUES
(43, 10, 30, 43, 1, 1, 2, 'I and my Father are one', 'Unity of Christ and God', 'Both passages emphasize the oneness of Christ and God. John 10:30 states, ''I and my Father are one,'' while John 1:1-2 affirms that ''the Word was God,'' indicating a shared divine nature.', 'theme', 0.7689999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 43, 14, 9, 9, 'I and my Father are one', 'Unity of Jesus and the Father', 'Both passages emphasize the unity between Jesus and the Father. In John 10:30, Jesus states, ''I and my Father are one,'' while in John 14:9, he explains that seeing him is equivalent to seeing the Father.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 40, 28, 19, 19, 'I and my Father are one.', 'Unity of Father and Son', 'This connection highlights the unity between the Father and the Son, as expressed in both passages. John 10:30 emphasizes their oneness, while Matthew 28:19 includes both in the baptismal formula, indicating their shared authority.', 'theme', 0.46799999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 40, 11, 27, 27, 'I and my Father are one', 'Unity of Father and Son', 'This connection highlights the relationship between the Father and the Son, as both passages emphasize their unity and mutual knowledge. In John 10:30, Jesus states, ''I and my Father are one,'' while Matthew 11:27 reflects on the exclusive knowledge shared between them.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 62, 5, 20, 20, 'I and my Father are one.', 'Unity of Christ and God', 'This connection highlights the unity between Jesus and God. Both passages emphasize the relationship of the Son with the Father, indicating that knowing the Son is essential to knowing the true God.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 56, 2, 13, 13, 'I and my Father are one', 'Unity of God and Christ', 'This connection highlights the unity between Jesus and God, as both passages emphasize the divine nature of Jesus. John 10:30 states, ''I and my Father are one,'' while Titus 2:13 refers to Jesus as ''the great God and our Saviour.''', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 30, 54, 3, 16, 16, 'I and my Father are one', 'Unity of God and Christ', 'This connection highlights the unity of God and Christ, as expressed in John 10:30 with ''I and my Father are one.'' In 1 Timothy 3:16, the manifestation of God in the flesh emphasizes the divine nature of Christ, suggesting a profound relationship between the two.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 43, 5, 18, 18, NULL, 'Hostility Towards Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' intent to kill Jesus due to his claims about his relationship with God. In John 5:18, they sought to kill him for making himself equal with God, while in John 10:31, they attempted to stone him, indicating ongoing hostility.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 43, 8, 59, 59, 'took up stones', 'Attempts to Stone Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Jews'' intent to stone Jesus. In each instance, the act of taking up stones signifies their rejection and hostility towards him. This connection highlights a recurring theme of conflict between Jesus and the Jewish leaders.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 9, 30, 6, 6, 'to stone him', 'Stoning and Distress', 'This connection highlights the theme of distress and the threat of stoning faced by both David and Jesus. In both passages, individuals are confronted with the anger of the people, leading to a moment of crisis. Both figures respond to the threat in their own ways, emphasizing reliance on God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 2, 17, 4, 4, 'to stone him', 'Threat of Stoning', 'Both passages emphasize the imminent threat of stoning faced by the leaders. In Exodus, Moses fears being stoned by the people, while in John, Jesus is confronted with the same fate from the Jews.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 40, 21, 35, 35, NULL, 'Violence Against God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the violent response to God''s messengers. In John, the Jews attempt to stone Jesus, while in Matthew, the husbandmen stone one of the servants.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 40, 23, 35, 35, NULL, 'Connection of Righteous Blood', 'This connection highlights the theme of violence against the righteous. Both passages emphasize the act of shedding blood, with John referencing the Jews'' intent to stone Jesus and Matthew recalling the blood of the righteous from Abel to Zacharias.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 31, 44, 7, 52, 52, 'to stone him', 'Persecution of the Just One', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the violent response of the people towards those who proclaim truth, culminating in the stoning of Jesus and the reference to slain prophets in Acts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 9, 19, 4, 6, 'good works', 'Innocence and Good Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of innocence and good works in both passages. In John 10:32, Jesus refers to his good works, while in 1 Samuel 19:4-6, Jonathan defends David''s good works and innocence against Saul''s intentions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 14, 24, 20, 22, 'for which of those works do ye stone me?', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'Both passages emphasize the stoning of a messenger of God. In John, Jesus questions why he is stoned despite his good works, paralleling Zechariah''s fate after delivering God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 19, 35, 12, 12, 'good works', 'Evil for Good Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being repaid with evil despite performing good works. In John 10:32, Jesus highlights His good works, while Psalms 35:12 speaks of being rewarded with evil for good actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 19, 109, 4, 5, 'good works', 'Connection of Adversity and Good Works', 'This connection highlights the theme of being rewarded with evil for good deeds. In John 10:32, Jesus refers to the good works He has done, while Psalms 109:4-5 speaks of adversaries responding with hatred despite love. Both passages emphasize the contrast between good actions and negative responses.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 21, 4, 4, 4, 'good works', 'Connection of Good Works and Envy', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''good works'' and the response they provoke from others. In John, Jesus highlights his good works as a reason for questioning, while Ecclesiastes reflects on how such works can lead to envy from neighbors.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 40, 11, 5, 5, 'good works have I shewed you', 'Connection of Good Works and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' miraculous works. Both passages emphasize the transformative acts of healing and preaching that demonstrate His divine authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 32, 43, 5, 19, 20, 'good works have I shewed you', 'Connection of Works and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and the Father in performing works. In John 10:32, Jesus refers to the good works he has shown, while in John 5:19-20, he explains that he does nothing apart from what he sees the Father do.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 43, 5, 18, 18, 'makest thyself God', 'Claims of Equality with God', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation of blasphemy against Jesus for claiming equality with God. In John 10:33, the Jews accuse Him of making Himself God, while in John 5:18, they react to His claim of God as His Father, interpreting it as making Himself equal with God.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 3, 24, 16, 16, 'blasphemy', 'Blasphemy and Punishment Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of blasphemy and its severe consequences. In John 10:33, the accusation of blasphemy leads to the intent to stone, paralleling Leviticus 24:16, which prescribes death for blasphemers.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 43, 10, 30, 30, 'makest thyself God', 'Unity of Christ and God', 'Both passages emphasize the relationship between Jesus and God. The claim of being ''one'' with the Father in John 10:30 leads to accusations of blasphemy in John 10:33, highlighting the perceived divine nature of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 19, 82, 6, 6, 'makest thyself God', 'Divine Identity and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine identity, as both passages address the concept of being ''gods.'' In John 10:33, the accusation of blasphemy arises from Jesus claiming a divine status, while Psalms 82:6 asserts that humans can be referred to as ''gods'' due to their relationship with the Most High.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 45, 13, 1, 1, NULL, 'Authority and Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority, as both passages address the nature of power. In John 10:33, the assertion of making oneself God challenges the understanding of divine authority, while Romans 13:1 emphasizes that all powers are ordained by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 50, 2, 6, 6, 'makest thyself God', 'Divine Equality and Blasphemy', 'This connection highlights the theme of divinity, as both passages address the concept of being equal with God. John 10:33 presents the accusation of blasphemy against Jesus for claiming divinity, while Philippians 2:6 affirms His equality with God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 33, 11, 21, 10, 10, 'blasphemy', 'Blasphemy and Stoning Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of blasphemy leading to stoning. In John 10:33, the accusation of blasphemy is made against Jesus, while 1 Kings 21:10 describes a similar scenario where false witnesses accuse someone of blasphemy, resulting in a death sentence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 19, 82, 6, 7, 'Ye are gods', 'Connection of Divine Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''Ye are gods,'' highlighting a shared theme of divine identity among humans. Additionally, they both address the consequences of this status, indicating a fallibility that leads to death.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 10, 34, 2, 7, 1, 1, 'Ye are gods', 'Divine Authority in Leadership', 'This connection highlights the concept of divine authority granted to leaders. Both passages emphasize the idea of being designated as ''gods'' or having god-like authority in their respective contexts.', 'theme', 0.524, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
